{{Infobox religious building | name = Kitabatake Shrine | image = Kitabatake Shrine.jpg | caption = Kitabatake Shrine | map_type = Japan | map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|34.51858|136.29885|type:landmark_region:JP|format=dms|display=title,inline}} | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | type = | deity = | founded_by = | established = 1643 | date_destroyed = | location = | website = | architecture_style = | festival = | leadership = }} '''Kitabatake Shrine''' (北畠神社, ''Kitabatake jinja'') is a [[Shinto]] shrine located in [[Tsu, Mie]] Prefecture, Japan. Its main festival is held annually on October 13. It was founded in 1643, and enshrines the [[kami]] of [[Kitabatake Akiyoshi]] as well as other members of the [[Kitabatake clan]]. It is one of the [[Fifteen Shrines of the Kenmu Restoration]].
==Tage Kitabatakeshi shi jo-kan (Kitabatake clan`s residence and castle)== Kitabatakeshi Yakata was fortified residence of Tage [[Kitabatake clan]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.info.city.tsu.mie.jp/www/contents/1001000011242/index.html |title=続日本100名城 |publisher=日本城郭協会|language=Japanese|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> Now Kitabatake Shrine is on site. But the garden made by Kitabatake clan is still remains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tsukanko.jp/spot/183/ |title=北畠氏館跡庭園|publisher=津市観光協会|language=Japanese|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> Also Kitabatake clan built Kiriyama Castle on the mountain behind Kitabatakeshi Yakata.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kojodan.jp/castle/1255/ |title=北畠氏館跡|publisher=攻城団|language=Japanese|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>Kiriyama Castle is now only ruins with some eathen walls and dry moat.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://shirobito.jp/castle/1719 |title=霧山城 |publisher=城びと|language=Japanese|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref>
Kitabatakeshi shi jo-kan (Kitabatake clan`s residence and castle) was listed as one of the [[Continued Top 100 Japanese Castles]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://jokaku.jp/japan-top-100-castles/best-100-castles-of-japan-2nd-selection/ |title=続日本100名城 |publisher=日本城郭協会|language=Japanese|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> [[File:Kiriyama Castle ruins.jpg|thumb|250px|Kiriyama Castle]]
==See also== *[[Fifteen Shrines of the Kenmu Restoration]] ==References== {{reflist}}
==External links== *[http://www.kankomie.or.jp/spot/detail_2928.html Prefectural tourism website]
